{{tone|date=August 2018}}
[[Facebook]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Netflix]] and [[Google]] ('''FAANG'''), a further extension of '''FANG''' (which originally did not include Apple), is both an acronym and a [[buzzword]] to entice investors, as popularised by [[Jim Cramer]] from [[CNBC]]'s [[Mad Money]] and other [[pundit|talking heads]] for grouping together currently high performance technology companies currently listed on [[NASDAQ]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thestreet.com/story/14320244/1/fang-stocks-index.html |title= FANG Stocks Are Getting Their Own Index |first= Kinsey |last= Grant|publisher= [[TheStreet.com|The Street]] |date= Sep 26, 2017 }}</ref> While it usually refers to the five (or four) of these technology companies specifically, the term is now generally used to refer to the technology and [[Luxury goods|consumer discretionary]] sectors consisting of highly-traded growth stocks of [[United States|American]] technology and tech-enabled companies in recent years.<ref name="fool">{{cite news |last1=Frankel |first1=Matthew |title=What Are the FANG Stocks? |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2017/09/29/ask-a-fool-what-are-the-fang-stocks.aspx |accessdate=11 August 2018 |work=[[Motley Fool]] |date=29 September 2017}}</ref> Such a perspective of the market demonstrates a huge impact with commensurate profit or loss.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/business/facebook-stock-market.html |title= Facebook and Other Tech Companies Drag Down Stock Markets |first= Matt |last= Phillips |work= The New York Times |date= Mar 19, 2018 }}</ref> Opinions have been divided over whether this phenomenon is indicative of a [[tech bubble]] or long-term sustained growth of these technology companies.<ref name="fool" />

In 2017, [[Intercontinental Exchange]] has initiated an index with this focus through the [[NYSE]] and extended FANG with [[Twitter]], [[Nvidia]] and [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]] and with BAT stocks, the [[China|Chinese]] counterparts: [[Baidu]], [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] and [[Tencent]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.barrons.com/articles/the-fangs-vs-the-bats-which-is-more-vulnerable-to-a-downturn-1523983900 |title= The FANGs vs. the BATs: Which Is More Vulnerable to a Downturn? |first= Reshma |last= Kapadia |date= April 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-08/fang-lovers-given-new-way-to-bet-on-stocks-with-futures-trading |title= FANG Lovers Get a New Way to Bet on Stocks With Futures Trading |first= Lu |last= Wang |date= Nov 8, 2017  |publisher= Barrons }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.investopedia.com/news/new-index-track-fang-stocks-nyse-ice-nyfang |title= New Index to Track FANG Stocks Will Launch in November [2017] |publisher= Investopedia |first= Nathan |last= Reiff |date= Sep 27, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= NYSE to Launch FANG+ Options on June 4; Offers Efficient Hedging and Exposure to Basket of Key Tech Stocks |url= https://www.nasdaq.com/press-release/nyse-to-launch-fang-options-on-june-4-offers-efficient-hedging-and-exposure-to-basket-of-key-tech-20180523-00716 |publisher= NASDAQ |series= Press release |date= May 23, 2018 }}</ref> Investment analysts have often compared FAANG against or together with BAT stocks due to the latter's similar level of growth in the Chinese stock market.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Jacky |title=BATs vs. FANGs: Why China’s Tech Has Extra Risk |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bats-vs-fangs-why-chinas-tech-has-extra-risk-1507870793 |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=13 October 2017}}</ref>

There are also actively managed [[Exchange-traded fund|ETF]]s, which attempt to take advantage of the phenomenon of these index-based funds, since indices don’t have the power to make adjustments on any given day. However, investors should be wary as an ETF may not be currently holding all of the implied tech company stocks. For example, the ETF known by ticker FNG, sold out of Facebook during the [[Facebook–Cambridge Analytica data scandal|Cambridge Analytica scandal]], but also dumped Apple holdings ahead of its earnings boost.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-26/-f-is-for-this-etf-is-named-after-fangs-and-holds-no-facebook |title= 'F' is for? This ETF is Named After FANGs and Holds No Facebook |first1= Carolina |last1= Wilson |first2= Sarah |last2= Frier |publisher= Bloomberg |date= July 26, 2018 }}</ref>

