{{papuan-lang-stub}} {{PapuaNewGuinea-stub}}

[[Rabbi]] '''Jacob ben Isaac Ashkenazi''' (1550–1625), of [[Janów Lubelski|Janów]] (near [[Lublin]], [[Poland]]), was the author of the ''[[Tseno Ureno]]'', sometimes called the "Women's [[Hebrew Bible|Bible]]", a [[Yiddish]]-language prose work written around the 1590s whose structure parallels the [[Parsha|weekly portions]] of the [[Pentateuch]] and [[Haftorah]]s used in [[Shabbat]] [[Jewish services#Shabbat services|services]].<ref name=Katz2007>{{Cite book |last=Katz |first=Dovid |title=Words on Fire: The Unfinished Story of Yiddish |edition=2 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York |year=2007 |isbn=0-465-03730-5 |page=95 |postscript=.}}</ref>
He also authored a supplement, the ''Melitz Yosher'' ({{hebrew|מליץ יושר}}) and ''Seyfer Ha Magid'' ({{hebrew|המגיד}}). ''Ha Magid'', which literally means "the book that tells" or "the messenger book" in the biblical sense, as in "the messenger came to David saying" in {{bibleverse|2|Samuel|15:13|HE}}, is a similar compilation on the [[Nevi'im|Prophets]] and [[Hagiographa]].<ref name=Katz2007 />
