'''The Tartan Curtain''' is a term of reference to the change in status of the Scottish border with [[England]] in the event that Scotland becomes an independent sovereign state, as supported by the [[Scottish national party|Scottish National Party]].

The term Tartan Curtain has the negative connotations of the [[Iron Curtain]] which divided [[Europe]] during the [[Cold War]].

The constitutional consequences of a newly independent [[Scotland]] joining the [[European union|EU]] remain unclear, but if Scotland has to join the [[European Union|EU]] as a new member state it will not necessarily inherit the vetoes enjoyed by the rest of the [[UK|United Kingdom]].
Part of the issue relates to the [[Schengen treaty]], which allows free movement between [[European Union]] member states. The [[United Kingdom]] exercises an opt out from this treaty in order to maintain complete control over its own border.

The [[House of Commons Foreign Affairs Committee]] report entitled "The foreign policy implications of and for a separate Scotland" contains the following quote as Written evidence from the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]:
"The impact of an independent Scotland joining Schengen, were it to wish or be obliged to do so, would be significant, creating a UK land border with the Schengen area for the first time (the Republic of Ireland is not a member of Schengen)."<ref>The House of Commons Foreign Affairs Committee report, "[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmfaff/writev/643/643.pdf The foreign policy implications of and for a separate Scotland]"</ref>

The term has been used in parliament, the press and in public discussions associated with Scottish Independence.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/party-address-1-801002 Party Address, The Scotsman, Thursday 22 April 2010]</ref><ref>[http://blogs.reuters.com/uknews/2011/05/19/measuring-up-the-tartan-curtain/ Measuring up the Tartan curtain, Reuters]</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmhansrd/vo041125/debtext/41125-09.htm Hansard, 25 Nov 2004 : Column 258]</ref>

The term itself could relate to an Independent [[Scotland]]'s physical [[Anglo-Scottish border|border]] with the rest of the [[UK]] as well as differences in the [[currency]] and membership of international organisations such as [[NATO]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-19993694 BBC News, SNP members asked to ditch party's anti-Nato policy]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-19997538 BBC News, Scottish independence: UK foreign policy 'may be put at short-term risk']</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/george-osborne-independent-scots-could-lose-pound-8114017.html The Independent, George Osborne: independent Scots could lose pound]</ref>

